    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="duaru[m] vocalium">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Audomarus Tala[e]us Veliam, oppidum Lucania[e],
                    </marginalia_text>   
                    <person name="Omer Talon"/>
                    <location name="Velia"/>
                    <location name="Lucania"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        ἀπὸ τοῦ ἕλεος
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        nomen habuisse refert, aspiratione in latina voce Versa in u vocalem.
                        grammatici nostri u consonantem vocant.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Audomarus Talaeus reports that Velia, the city in Lucania, had the name 'apo tou heleos', with the aspiration 
                turned in the Latin tongue into the vowel 'u'.
                Our grammaticians call 'u' a consonant.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Si iu, in Juno diphthongus esset, esset, ut uidetur, in Virgiliano carmine 
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Virgil"/>
                    <person name="Juno"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        συναλλοιφὴ.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        nisi forte
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        διαίρεσιν                     
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        esse putemus, et J&uuml;no sonandum arbitremur, quod nemo vnq[uam] obseruauit. Sed qui in his 
                        uocibus, aur&atiled;i, aqu&atiled;i, aul&atiled;i, pict&atiled;i, tam audacem, ut ita dicam, ferit
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        διαίρεσιν,
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        potuit etiam eadem licentia J&uuml;no dicere.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>            
            <translation>
                If the 'ju' in 'Juno' were a diphthong, it would - as is clear - undergo 'synalepha' in Virgil's poetry. Otherwise, we may suppose it undergoes
                'diaresis' and judge that it is to be pronounced 'I-uno', something that no-one has previously noticed. But one who, if I may say, were so bold as to
                use diaeresis with these vowels - 'aura-i', 'aqua-i', 'aula-i', 'picta-i' - could with the same wantonness say 'I-uno'.         
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
